file_documentation.NAME: non_ip_data_service.idl
file_documentation.DESCRIPTION:
This specification documents Major Version 1 of the Qualcomm Messaging 
  Interface (QMI) for NON IP data service(QMI_NIPD).The messages in
  this specification are specific to NON IP data transfer.

QMI_NIPD_INDICATION_REGISTER.BRIEF:
Sets the registration state for different QMI_NIPD indications
           for the requesting control point.
QMI_NIPD_INDICATION_REGISTER.ERROR:
-QMI_ERR_NONE              No error in the request
    -QMI_ERR_INTERNAL          Unexpected error occurred during processing
    -QMI_ERR_MALFORMED_MSG     Message was not formulated correctly by the
                               control point or the message was corrupted
                               during transmission
    -QMI_ERR_NO_MEMORY         Device could not allocate memory to formulate
                               a response   
    -QMI_ERR_MISSING_ARG       One or more required TLVs are missing in the request
QMI_NIPD_INDICATION_REGISTER.DESCRIPTION:
This command registers and deregisters a control point for different
QMI_NON_IP indications. The control point's event reporting state variables
are modified according to the settings specified in the TLVs included
in the request message.

If the Report Downlink Data TLV is enabled, the control point receives
downlink NON IP data via QMI_NIPD_DOWNLINK_DATA_IND indication.

QMI_GET_SUPPORTED_MSGS.DESCRIPTION:
This command queries the set of messages implemented by the currently 
  running software. This may be a subset of the messages defined in this
  revision of the service.
QMI_GET_SUPPORTED_MSGS.BRIEF:
Queries the set of messages implemented by the currently 
               running software.
QMI_GET_SUPPORTED_MSGS.ERROR:
-QMI_ERR_NONE              No error in the request        
    -QMI_ERR_INTERNAL          Unexpected error occurred during processing
    -QMI_ERR_NO_MEMORY         Device could not allocate memory to formulate 
                               a response
    -QMI_ERR_INFO_UNAVAILABLE  Information is not available

QMI_NIPD_GET_CAPABILITY.BRIEF: Queries the capabilities supported by the QMI_NIPD service.
QMI_NIPD_GET_CAPABILITY.DESCRIPTION:
This command queries the NON IP data service capability supported by the modem. 

The Maximum allowed payload length TLV indicates the maximum length of data that can be
transfered at a time using QMI_NIPD_DOWNLINK_DATA_IND and QMI_NIPD_UPLINK_DATA_REQ messages.
QMI_NIPD_GET_CAPABILITY.ERROR:
-QMI_ERR_NONE              No error in the request
    -QMI_ERR_INTERNAL          Unexpected error occurred during processing
    -QMI_ERR_NO_MEMORY         Device could not allocate memory to
                               formulate a response

QMI_NIPD_DOWNLINK_DATA_IND.DESCRIPTION:
This indication sends down link data to the control points which are registered
to Report Downlink Data via QMI_NIPD_INDICATION_REGISTER_REQ message.Indication 
contains NON IP data payload recevied from network. Control point must be bound 
to a specific data port or endpoint ID/mux ID to receive down link data. 

If the data needs to  be  segmented  across multiple QMI messages, the Segment 
Number TLV is used to indicate the segment number in the sequence which starts 
with 1 and monotonically increases for each subsequent segment.

For the last data segment in the sequence the Final Segment TLV will be set TRUE.

If the entire  NON IP  data  payload  can  be sent in one indication then Segment 
Number TLV and Final Segment TLV will be absent.
QMI_NIPD_DOWNLINK_DATA_IND.BRIEF: Send down link NON IP data to control point.

QMI_NIPD_BIND_CLIENT.BRIEF: Binds a control point to specified preferences
QMI_NIPD_BIND_CLIENT.ERROR:
-QMI_ERR_NONE              No error in the request
    -QMI_ERR_INTERNAL          Unexpected error occurred during processing
    -QMI_ERR_MALFORMED_MSG     Message was not formulated
                               correctly by the control point or the message
                               was corrupted during transmission 
    -QMI_ERR_MISSING_ARG       One or more required TLVs were missing in the request
    -QMI_ERR_INVALID_ARG       Specified value is invalid
    -QMI_ERR_NO_MEMORY         Device could not allocate memory to formulate
                               a response
    -QMI_ERR_NO_EFFECT         Binding has no effect
QMI_NIPD_BIND_CLIENT.DESCRIPTION:
This command binds the control point to specific parameters. 

Depending on the target, either data port or endpoint ID/mux ID is applicable.
A control point must be bound to a specific data port or endpoint ID/mux ID
before any other control/data messages are sent. Therefore, this command must be 
sent immediately after the client ID is assigned and before other control/data
messages are sent.

If the request contains the Binding Data Port TLV, the control point is bound to
the specified data port. The endpoint ID identifies the physical data 
channel, and the mux ID identifies the logical data channel to which the 
client binds.

After binding is complete, all the messages sent from or received on this 
control point are for the specified data port or endpoint ID/mux ID. 

If the control point has used the Bind Subscription TLV to specify the 
subscription, all further client-related operations are applied on this subscription.
If the client explicitly binds to the default subscription (DFS_DEFAULT_SUBS), 
all operations for this client are resolved with the current default 
data subscription on the modem.

QMI_NIPD_GET_CLIENT_BINDING.BRIEF: Gets all the preferences that the control point is bound to.
QMI_NIPD_GET_CLIENT_BINDING.ERROR:
-QMI_ERR_NONE              No error in the request
    -QMI_ERR_INTERNAL          Unexpected error occurred during processing
    -QMI_ERR_NO_MEMORY         Device could not allocate memory to formulate
                               a response
QMI_NIPD_GET_CLIENT_BINDING.DESCRIPTION:
This command retrieves the data port or endpoint ID/mux ID and 
subscription preference for the control point.

QMI_NIPD_UPLINK_DATA.ERROR:
-QMI_ERR_NONE              No error in the request
    -QMI_ERR_INTERNAL          Unexpected error occurred during processing
    -QMI_ERR_MALFORMED_MSG     Message was not formulated
                               correctly by the control point or the message
                               was corrupted during transmission 
    -QMI_ERR_MISSING_ARG       One or more required TLVs were missing in the request
    -QMI_ERR_INVALID_ARG       Specified value is invalid
    -QMI_ERR_NO_MEMORY         Device could not allocate memory to formulate
                               a response
    -QMI_ERR_OUT_OF_CALL       Request was issued when the packet data
                               session was disconnected
QMI_NIPD_UPLINK_DATA.DESCRIPTION:
This command sends NON IP uplink data to modem. Control point must be bound to 
a specific data port or endpoint ID/mux ID to send uplink data. 

If there is no  active call  on  that  data port,  a QMI_ERR_OUT_OF_CALL error
is returned.

If the data needs to  be segmented across  multiple  QMI messages, the Segment 
Number TLV is used to indicate the segment number in the sequence which starts
with 1 and monotonically increases for each subsequent segment.

For the last data segment in the sequence the Final Segment TLV should be set
TRUE.

If the entire NON IP data payload can be sent in one request then Segment 
Number TLV and Final Segment TLV should be absent.
QMI_NIPD_UPLINK_DATA.BRIEF: Sends uplink NON IP data to modem.

QMI_GET_SUPPORTED_FIELDS.DESCRIPTION:
This command queries the fields supported for a single command as implemented
  by the currently running software.

  If the request, response, or indication is supported for the given message ID, 
  the corresponding optional array is included in 
  QMI_<SVC>_GET_SUPPORTED_FIELDS_RESP, even if the message does not contain any 
  optional fields. This enables the client to distinguish this case from one 
  where the service does not support the request, response, or indication.  

  Examples are:\begin{itemize}

  \item If the specified message ID is not supported by the service, the 
        response has qmi_result = QMI_RESULT_FAILURE and qmi_error = 
        QMI_ERR_REQUESTED_NUM_UNSUPPORTED.

  \item If the specified message ID is an empty message, the response 
        has qmi_result = QMI_RESULT_SUCCESS and qmi_error = QMI_ERR_NONE.
        None of the optional arrays are included.

  \item If the specified message ID supports the request with 0 optional 
        fields, the response with 3 optional fields (16, 17, and 18 decimal), 
        and does not support an indication, the response has the 
        following:\begin{itemize}
  
        \item qmi_result = QMI_RESULT_SUCCESS
        \item qmi_error = QMI_ERR_NONE
        \item request_fields array is included with length zero 
        \item response_fields array is included with length 1 value [07]
        \item indication_fields array is not included
        \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}

  Trailing zero bytes are omitted from the response. For example,
  if the message defines 20 different fields but the response only contains 16 
  bits, the client is to assume the last four fields are not supported.
QMI_GET_SUPPORTED_FIELDS.BRIEF:
Queries the fields supported for a single command as implemented 
               by the currently running software.
QMI_GET_SUPPORTED_FIELDS.ERROR:
-QMI_ERR_NONE                        No error in the request        
    -QMI_ERR_INTERNAL                    Unexpected error occurred during 
                                         processing
    -QMI_ERR_NO_MEMORY                   Device could not allocate memory to 
                                         formulate a response
    -QMI_ERR_REQUESTED_NUM_UNSUPPORTED   Requested message ID is not supported by
                                         the currently running software 
    -QMI_ERR_MALFORMED_MSG               Message was not formulated correctly by the 
                                         control point or the message was corrupted 
                                         during transmission
    -QMI_ERR_INFO_UNAVAILABLE            Information is not available

elementlist.valuedescription: \n Downlink data payload.

Set to TRUE when current seqment is final 
       segment of a sequence. Default value: FALSE\n
Current seqment number of a sequence. \n

Standard response type. Contains the following data members:
     - qmi_result_type -- QMI_RESULT_SUCCESS or QMI_RESULT_FAILURE \n
     - qmi_error_type  -- Error code. Possible error code values are described 
                          in the error codes section of each message definition.

This field describes which optional field IDs are supported in the QMI 
       request. The array of uint8 is a bitmask where each bit represents a 
       field (TLV) ID. Because fields 0 to 15 (decimal) are mandatory by 
       definition, the first bit represents field ID 16. Starting with the 
       LSB, bit 0 represents field ID 16, bit 1 represents field ID 17, etc. 
       
       \vspace{3pt}
       The bit is set to 1 if the field ID is supported; otherwise, it is set 
       to zero. 
       
       \vspace{3pt}
       For example, if a service supports exactly four fields with 
       IDs 16, 17, 30, and 31 (decimal), the array (in hexadecimal) is 
       2 bytes [03 c0].

This field describes which optional field IDs are supported in the QMI 
       response. Its format is the same as request_fields.

This field describes which optional field IDs are supported in the QMI 
       indication. Its format is the same as request_fields.

Result code
                            - QMI_RESULT_SUCCESS
                            - QMI_RESULT_FAILURE

Error code. Possible error code values are 
                               described in the error codes section of each 
                               message definition.
ID of the command for which the supported fields are requested.
Standard response type.
